    slug: "the-new-kids-map",
    category: "Drama",
    emoji: "🗺️",
    excerpt: "On his first day at a new school, Omar drew a map to survive lunch, never expecting it to change someone's life.",
    created_at: "2026-04-22T12:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Omar had switched schools four times in three years. He had a system now. On his first day he drew a map of the cafeteria, marking the safest place to sit alone, the quickest exit, the table to avoid.</p><p>He found his corner and ate in silence, the way he always did. But this time he noticed a girl across the room doing the exact same thing, hunched over a sketchbook, eating fast, eyes down. He recognized that look. It was his own.</p><p>For two days he watched her sit alone. On the third day, before he could talk himself out of it, he slid his map across her table. He had added a new mark in the corner: a little star, labeled good spot, two chairs.</p><p>She stared at it. Then, slowly, she smiled and pulled out the chair beside her own.</p><p>Her name was Lena, and she had been the only new kid until Omar arrived. They spent lunch trading stories of all the schools they had each survived. She drew a tiny version of him on his own map, sitting at her table, no longer alone.</p><p>Omar kept that map long after he stopped needing it. Years later it was worn soft at the folds, the star in the corner faded but still there. He had drawn it to survive one lonely lunch. It had given him his first real friend instead.</p>",
