    slug: "when-the-lights-went-out",
    category: "Drama",
    emoji: "🕯️",
    excerpt: "A citywide blackout left Aanya stuck in a dark apartment with the elderly neighbor she had always been told to avoid.",
    created_at: "2026-04-21T18:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>The power died with a hum and a click, and the whole city went black. Aanya was alone in the hallway, fumbling for her keys, when a voice spoke from the next doorway.</p><p>It was Mr. Greer, the old man from 4B, the one neighborhood kids whispered was grumpy and strange. Aanya had never spoken to him. But he held a lit candle, and his voice was kind. Come sit, he said. No sense being scared in the dark alone.</p><p>So she sat in his doorway, and they waited together. To pass the time, Mr. Greer told stories, of the war he had lived through, of the wife he had lost, of a blackout sixty years ago when neighbors had played music in the streets.</p><p>Aanya realized she had judged a whole person by a rumor. He was not grumpy. He was lonely, which was a very different thing.</p><p>When the lights finally flickered back, neither of them moved right away. The candle had burned low, and the stories were not finished.</p><p>After that night, Aanya visited Mr. Greer every week. She brought him tea and listened to his stories, and he taught her chess and how to whistle properly. He told her once that the blackout had been the best thing to happen to him in years. Aanya understood. Sometimes the lights have to go out before you really see someone.</p>",
