    category: "Drama",
    emoji: "✉️",
    excerpt: "Every day Jonah found a tiny note in his lunchbox, until the day the notes stopped coming.",
    created_at: "2026-04-21T00:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Since first grade, Jonah had found a note in his lunchbox every single day. Little ones, on napkins or torn paper. You are braver than you know. I am proud of you. Have a great day, kiddo. They were from his dad, who packed his lunch each morning before the early shift.</p><p>By twelve, Jonah found them embarrassing. He stopped reading them. He shoved them in his pocket and threw them away, sometimes without even unfolding them.</p><p>Then one autumn his dad got sick, the kind of sick that meant long stays at the hospital. The lunchboxes after that were packed by Jonah himself, and they were silent. No notes. He had not realized how much the small words had filled him until they were gone.</p><p>One afternoon, cleaning his room, he found a shoebox under his bed. Inside were hundreds of the notes he thought he had thrown away. His mother, it turned out, had been quietly fishing them from his pockets and saving them for years.</p><p>Jonah read every one, sitting on his floor until the light faded.</p><p>The next morning he visited the hospital with a napkin in his hand. On it he had written, in careful letters, the words his father had given him so many times. You are braver than you know. I am proud of you.</p><p>His dad read it, smiled, and tucked it into his own pocket. Some letters, Jonah learned, are meant to travel both ways.</p>",
