    category: "Romance",
    emoji: "☔",
    excerpt: "Caught in the same downpour every Tuesday, two shy classmates slowly learned to share more than an umbrella.",
    created_at: "2026-04-18T18:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>It rained every Tuesday that spring, and every Tuesday, Sana and Kabir ended up at the same bus stop with the same problem. Her umbrella had a broken spoke. His turned inside out in the wind. Neither one worked properly alone.</p><p>The first Tuesday they stood apart, getting soaked, too shy to speak. The second Tuesday, Kabir held his battered umbrella over both of them without a word. Sana smiled at her shoes.</p><p>By the third Tuesday they were talking. About school, about books, about how strange it was that the rain only seemed to come on the day they both happened to be there. They discovered they both loved old movies and both hated math homework with a deep and noble passion.</p><p>The Tuesdays became the best part of Sana's week. She found herself hoping for clouds, checking the sky each morning, a little disappointed by sunshine.</p><p>Then came a Tuesday with no rain at all. Sana walked to the bus stop anyway, and there was Kabir, standing under the clear sky, holding his broken umbrella open over nothing.</p><p>I know it is not raining, he said, turning red. I just did not want to miss our Tuesday.</p><p>Sana laughed and stepped under the umbrella with him, where there was no rain to hide from, only the two of them, choosing to stand close. From then on, they shared the walk home every day, rain or shine.</p>",
