    excerpt: "Noor made a playlist for her best friend and accidentally sent it to the wrong boy entirely.",
    created_at: "2026-04-17T06:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Noor spent hours making the perfect cheer-up playlist for her best friend Zoya, who was having a rough week. She typed in the name to share it, hit send, and felt proud of herself.</p><p>Then her phone buzzed. The message was not from Zoya. It was from Aarav, a boy in her class she barely knew, whose name happened to start the same way as Zoya's in her contacts. His reply read: I did not know you liked this song too. It is my favorite. Thank you, this made my whole day.</p><p>Noor's face went hot. She started to explain the mistake, then stopped. Because Aarav had kept typing. He sent back a song of his own, then another, building a little playlist in return. Each one was thoughtful, the kind of music she actually loved.</p><p>So instead of correcting it, she answered with a song. He answered with two. For a week they traded music back and forth, never quite admitting it had started as an accident, both of them too happy to care.</p><p>Finally Aarav asked if she wanted to listen to records at the music shop on Saturday. Noor said yes before she could overthink it.</p><p>She did eventually tell Zoya, who laughed for ten minutes straight and declared it the best wrong number in history. Noor agreed. Sometimes, she decided, the best things arrive entirely by mistake, delivered to exactly the right person after all.</p>",
