    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>Pip folded a boat from yesterday's newspaper and wrote a tiny message inside the hull: I hope you have a good day, whoever you are.</p><p>The gutter outside was a rushing river after the storm. Pip set the boat down and watched it spin away, past the bakery, past the shoe shop, bobbing bravely over twigs and leaves.</p><p>Down the hill it sailed, where old Mr. Khan was sweeping his doorstep with a heavy heart. His cat had wandered off three days ago, and the house felt far too quiet.</p><p>The little boat snagged against his broom. Curious, he unfolded the soggy paper and read the message. He had not smiled in days, but he smiled then.</p><p>Just as he did, a faint meow came from the hedge. There, muddy and blinking, sat his cat, drawn out by the sound of someone finally laughing again.</p><p>Mr. Khan never learned who sent the boat. But the next rainy day, he folded one of his own and wrote inside: Thank you. Then he set it sailing up the hill, hoping it would find its way home.</p>",
