    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>The spring concert was tomorrow, and disaster had struck. A burst pipe had flooded the music room, soaking every drum, recorder, and triangle the school owned.</p><p>The other kids groaned. But quiet Noor, who rarely raised her hand, opened her backpack and pulled out a wrinkled sock with two googly eyes glued on.</p><p>We can still make a show, she said softly. Just not with instruments.</p><p>By morning the whole class had made sock puppets, each with its own funny voice. Noor wrote a story where the puppets hummed, clapped, stomped, and sang. She stood at the front and waved a pencil like a conductor's baton.</p><p>The hum-buzz of the high socks, the boom-stomp of the low socks, the click of clapping hands, it all wove together into something nobody had heard before. The audience leaned in, delighted.</p><p>When the final note faded, the gym roared with applause. The principal said it was the most original concert in the school's history.</p><p>Noor blushed all the way to her ears. She had always thought her quiet ideas were too small to matter. Now she knew that sometimes the quietest kid simply hears a different kind of music.</p>",
