    author: "Khyati Srivastava",
    slug: "the-lighthouse-that-forgot",
    category: "Inspirational",
    emoji: "🗼",
    excerpt: "An old lighthouse believes its light is useless now, until one storm proves the difference one beam can make.",
    created_at: "2026-04-11T06:00:00Z",
    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>On a rocky point stood an old lighthouse named Beren. For a hundred years he had guided ships home. But a new electric beacon was built down the coast, and slowly the boats stopped looking his way.</p><p>I am useless now, Beren sighed to the gulls. My light is old and dim. Nobody needs me.</p><p>The gulls had no answer, so they simply roosted on his railing and kept him company.</p><p>One autumn night a fierce storm rolled in. Rain hammered the cliffs, and the new beacon, struck by lightning, went dark. Out on the churning water, a small fishing boat lost its way, spinning toward the rocks.</p><p>Beren felt the boat's fear in his old stones. With everything he had, he flickered his tired lamp on, off, on, off.</p><p>The fisherman saw the faint blinking through the rain and steered toward it. Inch by inch, the boat slipped past the rocks and into the safe harbor.</p><p>At dawn the fisherman climbed the hill and pressed his hand to the cold wall. You saved us, he whispered. Your light was small, but it was enough.</p><p>Beren glowed with quiet pride. He understood at last that being needed less often did not mean being needed never.</p>",
