    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>In the attic of an old house lived a small ghost named Wobble. For two hundred years his job had been to gently say boo and make the floorboards creak. But one morning he woke up and could not remember how to say boo at all.</p><p>All that came out was a squeak, like a mouse with the hiccups.</p><p>This was a terrible problem, because a new family had just moved in, with two curious children named Tomas and Lin. A ghost who cannot boo, Wobble fretted, is barely a ghost at all.</p><p>That night Tomas and Lin heard the squeaking and tiptoed up to the attic, not scared but giggling. There floated Wobble, looking glum and slightly see-through.</p><p>The children were not frightened in the least. Instead they offered to help him practice. Lin puffed out her cheeks. Tomas waved his arms like a spooky tree. Together they boomed a great, silly BOO.</p><p>Wobble laughed so hard that, quite by accident, a proper booo slipped right out of him, rattling a window.</p><p>You did it, cheered the children.</p><p>From then on, Wobble only ever boo-ed to say hello. And every Friday, the most haunted attic in town was also the most full of laughter.</p>",
