    body: "<p style='color:#6a4b8f;font-style:italic;margin-bottom:18px'>By Khyati Srivastava</p><p>The Mehta family loved their new old house, except for one strange thing. Every night at exactly nine o'clock, the doorbell rang. And every night, when they opened the door, no one was there.</p><p>Ding-dong, said the bell. Empty porch, said the night.</p><p>Twins Aria and Veer decided to solve the mystery. They hid behind the curtains one evening, flashlights ready, eyes glued to the front step.</p><p>At nine exactly, the bell rang. But the porch stayed empty, just as always. Aria, however, noticed something. A faint shimmer near the doorframe, low to the ground, about the height of a small dog.</p><p>The next night they left a bowl of water and a soft blanket on the porch. When the bell rang, they peeked out, and there, faint and silvery, sat a translucent little terrier, wagging a see-through tail, nudging the bell button with its nose.</p><p>It was the ghost of a dog who had once lived there and still came home each night, ringing to be let in.</p><p>The twins opened the door wide and patted the blanket. Come in, they said gently.</p><p>The little ghost trotted inside, curled up, and gave a happy sigh. The doorbell never rang on its own again, because at last, someone had answered.</p>",
